That link is the new template — the current project is unchanged and is not the template. Tell the user to open the link and go to the Template Info tab to fill in title/description/preview and publish it to their org.`}},l8={name:"set_project_title",description:"Rename the current project. Use once you've identified a brand or product name so the project is findable in the org picker instead of sitting under a generic placeholder. No-op if the user has already named it.",input_schema:ve({title:pe("New project name — short, descriptive, human-readable")},["title"]),async execute(e,{projectId:t}){const n=String(e.title||"").trim();if(!n)return"Error: title is required";const r=ul(t)?.name?.trim()??"";if(!i8.has(r))return`Project already named "${r}" — leaving as-is.`;try{await $n.renameProject(t,n)}catch(s){return`Error renaming project: ${tI(s)}`}return`Project renamed to "${n}".`}},c8=[a8,l8],u8="omelette-settings",DB={flash:"gemini-2.5-flash-image",pro:"gemini-3-pro-image-preview"},ZB=1024,d8={name:"generate_image",description:`Generate image(s) using Google's Gemini image generation via the REST API. Writes results to the project's scraps/ folder. Supports text-to-image and image editing (pass an existing image as input).

This tool runs IN THE BACKGROUND. It returns immediately with a placeholder; the actual result (file paths in scraps/) arrives as a follow-up message when generation completes. You can continue with other work while it runs — don't sit idle waiting.

IMPORTANT: Always batch all your image generations into a single tool call by putting multiple descriptions in the prompts array. Do NOT make several sequential generate_image calls — the tool fires all prompts concurrently so a single call is both faster and cheaper.

Stylistic instructions: images you generate should match the brand + stylistic palette of your project. Pass in hex codes, fonts, other descriptions of the aesthetic of the project when generating.

Arguments:
- prompts (array of strings, required): One or more text descriptions or editing instructions. Each prompt is sent as its own API request, all running concurrently.
